That can certainly be a powerful incentive for some people and institutions. Many leaders, organizations, and movements care not only about immediate outcomes but also about how they’ll be remembered decades from now. Legacy can shape decisions just as much as short-term gains.

At the same time, it’s worth being cautious about universal claims like “they will do anything.” Different actors have different motives and constraints. Some may aggressively manage their public image or historical narrative, while others prioritize policy goals, personal principles, electoral success, financial incentives, or institutional stability.

One pattern that does recur across history is this:

* Short-term power is about influencing today’s decisions.
* Long-term legacy is about influencing tomorrow’s story.
* The more someone values legacy, the more they’ll often invest in archives, speeches, memoirs, monuments, media, education, and symbolism—not just immediate victories.

That’s why narrative is often contested alongside events themselves. Competing groups aren’t only asking, “Who wins today?” They’re also asking, “How will future generations interpret what happened?”

The interesting counterweight is that durable legacies usually depend on more than controlling the story. They also depend on evidence surviving scrutiny over time. New records emerge, historians revisit assumptions, and perspectives change. So while people may try to shape their legacy, they don’t have complete control over how later generations will judge it.

In that sense, there are really two games running in parallel:

* the power game (what happens now), and
* the legacy game (what endures in memory).

They influence each other, but they aren’t identical. History shows examples of people who won one and lost the other, as well as people whose reputations changed dramatically long after they were gone.